text: Office Safety 1 Office Safety Introduction Accidents may seem unlikely in an office environment when compared to construction jobsites or manufacturing plants, but an office has hazards too. Most office hazards are controllable and can be eliminated. Many office accidents happen when we take shortcuts, do not keep things in their proper place, do not pay attention to the task at hand, or when there is equipment that is faulty or not properly safeguarded. According to the Bureau of Labor

Statistics, 76,000 office workers in the United States receive disabling injuries each year. These include falls, electric shock, musculoskeletal disorders such as carpal tunnel syndrome, and more. The leading types of disabling accidents by percentage that occur within the office are: • Falls ….38% • Strains and over-exertion….25% • Struck by or striking objects ….18% • Caught in or between objects….12% • Other office related accidents….7% Which include foreign substances in the eyes, spilled

hot liquids, burns from fire, and electric shock. In recent years, illness has increased among the office worker population. This may be attributed, in part, to the increased presence of environmental toxins within the office and to stress-producing factors associated with the automated office. Resulting illnesses may include respiratory problems, skin diseases, and stress-related conditions. Office Furniture Hazard Controls Serious injuries can result from: defective furniture, misuse of

chairs, desks, or filing cabinets and improper use of step stools and ladders. Chairs • Do not climb on any office chair; instead use an appropriately rated step stool or ladder. • Chairs should be properly designed and regularly inspected for missing casters and loose parts. • Do not lean back in an office chair with your feet up. • Do not scoot across the floor while sitting in a chair. Office Safety 2 Filing Cabinets • Open only one file drawer at a time. • Do not locate file cabinets close

to doorways or in aisles. • Use drawer handles to close file drawers. Desks • Keep desks in good condition, free from sharp edges, nails or other areas of risk. • Keep desk drawers closed when not in use. Ladders • Ensure that ladder is in good condition and inspected regularly. • Be sure the ladder is fully open, and the spreaders are locked. • Place the ladder on slip-free surface. • Keep the area around ladder free of debris. • Maintain three points of contact at all times. • Do not use the

top two steps on a step ladder or ladder. Office Ergonomics Ergonomics is defined as the study of people in their working environment. The goal is to eliminate discomfort and risk of injury due to work. Hazards to watch for and avoid: • Sitting forward in your chair. • Pressure on the front edge of the thigh. • Wrists at an angle while typing or resting on a hard or sharp surface while typing. • Arms out, stretched in front or to the side while typing. • Head bent forward while reading printed

material or viewing the computer screen. Tips to help setup a safe and comfortable workstation to reduce the risk of potential musculoskeletal injuries in five steps. Step 1. Adjust your chair, if your workstation requires you to sit, or adjust your table height if possible when you must stand and there is no chair available. Making these adjustments will promote good a neutral posture. When seated neutral posture is defined as: • Feet resting comfortably on the floor or footrest. • Thighs fully

supported by your chair seat. • Hip angle of 90 to 110 degrees with your knees slightly lower than your hips. • Chair backrest supporting the natural curve of your back. • Upper arms resting comfortably at your sides with elbows at a 90 to 100- degree angle . • Straight and flat wrists. Office Safety 3 • Head centered over your neck and shoulders. Neutral standing posture is defined as: • Feet resting comfortably on the floor. • Knees unlocked. • Upper arms resting comfortably at your sides with

your elbows at a 90 to 100- degree angle. • Straight and flat wrists. • Head centered over your neck and shoulders. Step 2. Position work tools, including your keyboard, mouse, and phone, within easy reach so your elbows can rest comfortably at your sides when using them. Step 3. Avoid “cradling” your telephone handset between your shoulder and ear. Consider using a headset or speaker instead to prevent neck related injuries. Step 4. Ensure your monitor and document holder are positioned to

allow neutral posture of your head and neck. Step 5. Remember to frequently change positions. Incorporating movement into the workday is essential to allow for muscle recovery, improve blood flow, increase energy, and enhance productivity. For every hour worked sitting, it is good to spend five minutes walking or stretching to prevent muscle related injuries. Lighting and Office Safety Safety at work is one of the biggest concerns for any business owner. The lighting of any property can hugely

influence personal well-being, health, motivation, and performance. In the workplace, lighting has to meet occupational safety and health requirements. What has to be taken into consideration when it comes to office lighting is not just the aesthetics of how the lighting is incorporated into the building but the impact it has on the employees. Poor lighting can cause problems such as insufficient, glare, improper contrast, poorly distributed light, and flicker. Noise and Office Safety Unlike

many workplaces, the office is a relatively quiet place to work. Two important benefits of good office acoustics are the ability to concentrate without being distracted, and the ability to hear the spoken word. Noise is a productivity issue as much as it is a safety issue. Office Safety 4 The distinction between a sound and a noise is very subjective. It is particular to each person, and relative to the time and place. Noise is best described as any unwanted, loud, unexpected, or undesired

sound. What may be a pleasant sound to one person, such as a stereo playing jazz, may be an unpleasant noise to another. Acceptable levels will vary with the individuals in the office. While it is unlikely that noise levels in offices will reach damaging levels, noise can: • Create physical and psychological stress; • Reduce productivity; • Interfere with communication and concentration. Noise may be a problem in your workplace if you: • Hear ringing or humming in your ears when you leave work.

• Have to shout to be heard by a coworker an arm's length away. • Experience hearing problems shortly after leaving work. Sources of noise in the office include printers, phones, radios, voices, fax machines, computers, high foot traffic, Ventilation/Heating Systems. Noise can be reduced by: • Choosing the quiet equipment; • Maintaining equipment; • Reducing the ring volumes on phones; • If radios are allowed, keeping volumes low; • Placing noisy equipment in a separate room or as far away from

workstations as possible; • Rearrange work areas to isolate foot traffic; • Carpet, walls, and cubicles can help dampen noise. Indoor Air Quality The quality of indoor air inside offices is important not only for the employees’ comfort but also for their health. Poor indoor air quality or IAQ has been tied to symptoms like headaches, fatigue, trouble concentrating, and irritation of the eyes, nose, throat, and lungs. Also, some specific diseases have been linked to specific air contaminants or

indoor environments, like asthma with damp indoor environments. In addition, some exposures, such as asbestos and radon, do not cause immediate symptoms but can lead to cancer after many years. Many factors affect IAQ. Examples of these are ventilation, smoking and vehicle exhaust, mold, office supplies and personal products that can cause respiratory and eye irritation. Office Safety 5 Electrical Equipment Safety in the Office Electrical equipment used in office areas can be potentially

hazardous and cause electrical shock or fires if improperly maintained. Basic Electrical Safety Precautions • Electrical equipment must be maintained in good operating condition. • Equipment must have all panels and covers securely affixed. • If equipment is defective, take it out of service immediately. • Wall outlets must have the wall plates affixed. • Combustible material, such as paper, may not be stored on or in close proximity to electrical outlets. and • When not in use, turn off

electrical appliances such as coffee pots, computers, photocopiers, and heaters. • Check if Cords, Plugs, and Outlets are in Good Condition. • Cords must be Properly Placed to Prevent Damage. Safety Recommendations when using a Portable Space Heater: • Space heaters should be limited to small personal office areas only. • If possible, have maintenance make temperature adjustments to your area. • If a portable space heater is used, it must have: • A grounded three prong plug. • A maximum rating

of 1500 watts or 13 amps. • Auto tip-over shut-off feature. • Clearances of 36” in front and 18” on sides and back or in accordance with the manufacturer’s recommendations. • Do not plug heaters into extension cords or power strips. They must be plugged directly into a wall outlet to prevent hazards. Office Equipment Safeguarding Any Office Equipment, function, or process which may cause injury must be safeguarded. Examples of Office Equipment that might require safeguarding are the following: •

Copiers that have sorting trays and moving parts; • Guillotine Paper Cutters; • Letter openers and sharp tools like precision knives, scissors, and similar. Slips, Trips, and Falls Slips happen when there is not enough friction or traction between your feet and the surface you are walking on. Common causes of slips include wet or oily floors, spills, loose, or unanchored mats etc. Office Safety 6 Trips happen when your foot strikes an object, causing you to lose your balance. An employee can

trip due to a variety of reasons, including clutter in walkways, poor lighting, uncovered cables, drawers being left open, and wrinkled carpeting or rugs. Follow steps below to prevent slips and trips: • Clean up spills immediately. If a spill cannot be cleaned up right away, place “wet floor” warning signs for employees. • Keep walkways and hallways free of debris, clutter, and obstacles. • Keep filing cabinets and desk drawers shut when not in use. • Cover cables or cords in walkways. •

Replace burnt-out light bulbs promptly. • Consider installing abrasive floor mats or replacing worn flooring. • Encourage employees to wear comfortable, properly fitted shoes. Falls can happen in all occupational settings, and frequently involve slippery, cluttered, or unstable walking or working surfaces, unprotected edges, floor holes and wall openings, unsafely positioned ladders and issued fall protection. Methods to reduce the risk of falling at work: • Pay attention to surroundings; • Walk

at a pace that is suitable for the surface you are on; • Walk with your feet pointed slightly outward; • Make wide turns when walking around corners; • Use the handrails on stairs. Proper Attire Dress codes help employers fulfill varying goals of professionalism, comfort, safety, brand, and image. A few recommendations that are worth mentioning: • Wear loose, comfortable clothing to allow free movement of hips & to maintain natural spinal curves. • Avoid open-toed shoes and sandals, whenever

possible. • Wear comfortable footwear with a low heel to reduce leg and back strain and to prevent slips and falls. Housekeeping Recognize the Hazards: • Employees trip, fall, strike, or are struck by out-of-place objects. • Injuries from using improper tools because the correct tool cannot be found. • Lowered production because of the time spent maneuvering over and around someone else’s mess, and time spent looking for proper tools and materials. • Time spent investigating and reporting

accidents that could have been avoided. Safety procedures: Office Safety 7 • Clean up after yourself. • Pick up your trash and debris and dispose of it properly. • Have a place for everything and put everything in its place. • Store items straight and square. • Stack materials orderly and secure them so they will not topple. • Implement a routine cleaning schedule. • Keep your work area clean throughout the day. This will minimize the amount of time needed to clean a “larger mess” at the end of

the day. An uncluttered workplace shows respect for those who work at your place. Help keep it clean. Materials Handling in the Office Office duties may require risky movements that often result in back or other injuries. However, injuries can be avoided by following a few simple guidelines: • Never carry loads which obscure your clear view ahead; • Always maintain sight of where you are stepping; • Do not lift when your grip is awkward or unsecure; • Ensure your footing is stable; • Never lift

heavy loads above the shoulders; • Avoid bending by arranging your workstation at waist level; • Limit weight lifted to what you can only carry comfortably without strain; • Best lifting and carrying zone is between the shoulders and waist. Material Handling Aids are a great way to prevent injuries, and their use is recommended when appropriate, examples include: • Use a pushcart, hand-truck, or dolly for heavier loads; • Always secure the load to prevent shifting during movement; • Push the

load straight ahead; pulling the load results in twisting at the torso which increases the risk of injury; • Never store materials on top of cabinets or in aisles or walkways; • Heavy objects stored on lower shelves and materials should be stacked neatly; • Flammable and combustible materials should be identified and properly stored to prevent damage and potential injuries of personnel. Personal Protective Equipment is an important element that should not be overlooked when it comes to the

overall safety in the office environment: • Wear suitable gloves when handling materials with sharp edges; • Wear safety glasses when removing banding from around packages. Understanding Fire Safety and Emergency Plans • Know where the fire extinguishers are located and how to use them. Office Safety 8 • Extinguishers should be inspected monthly to ensure availability when they are needed. • Never block access to fire extinguishers and emergency exits. • Exits and access to exits must be marked.

• Make sure that all emergency exits are kept clear of snow and ice and that door hardware is in working condition. • Become familiar with your office emergency procedures in the event of a fire, storm, workplace violence, medical problem, or other emergency. • Know your company’s evacuation procedures, exit routes, and location of first aid supplies.
